{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568131"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19520"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19520"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.64,0.06,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85792"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12290"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70092"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2393"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29434"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85792"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Examination of her hands reveals separation of several fingernails from their nail beds, with the separation beginning at the distal margin (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate term to describe these nail changes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Onychomycosis","Onycholysis","Onychocryptosis","Onychogryphosis","Onychophosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows separation of the nail plate from the nail bed, which is termed \u003Cstrong\u003Eonycholysis\u003C/strong\u003E. This typically begins at the distal margin and progresses proximally. The separated portion often appears white or opaque due to air beneath the nail plate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnychomycosis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to fungal infection of the nail unit, which can cause thickening, discolouration, and brittleness of the nail. While it can lead to onycholysis, the primary changes seen here are not typical of fungal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnychocryptosis\u003C/strong\u003E, commonly known as ingrown toenail, occurs when the nail edge grows into the surrounding soft tissue, causing pain and inflammation. This is not demonstrated in the image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnychogryphosis\u003C/strong\u003E describes a thickened, curved nail deformity often resembling a ram\u0027s horn. This typically occurs in elderly people or following chronic trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnychophosis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to calloused tissue beneath the nail plate, typically seen in response to chronic pressure or friction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnycholysis has multiple potential causes including repetitive trauma (such as frequent typing or manicuring), infection (particularly \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E species), and systemic conditions including hyperthyroidism, psoriasis, and iron deficiency. The presence of onycholysis should prompt consideration of these underlying conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Onycholysis refers to separation of the nail plate from the nail bed, typically starting at the distal margin.","Common causes of onycholysis include trauma, infection, and systemic conditions like hyperthyroidism.","The presence of onycholysis should prompt consideration of underlying systemic conditions."],"references":["Lee DK, Lipner SR. Optimal diagnosis and management of common nail disorders. Ann Med. 2022;54(1):694-712. doi:10.1080/07853890.2022.2044511","Ngan V. Onycholysis. DermNet. Updated December 2020. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/onycholysis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70092"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19520"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21607"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21607"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MTvc4HGFnt8FqpTH1p1RsKd84XVPcx.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MTvc4HGFnt8FqpTH1p1RsKd84XVPcx.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":472}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70092"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-17T20:58:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-17T20:59:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12290"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85792"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"e